        "trailText":"Minister wanted to use his iPad in his Westminster office, but got frustrated &ndash; so he set up his own network. By <strong>Alex Hern</strong>",
        "headline":"Francis Maude installs Wi-Fi network to bypass 'rubbish' government IT",
        "body":"<p>Francis Maude, the Cabinet Office minister, is so frustrated with the state of government IT that he has installed his own Wi-Fi network in his Westminster office.</p> <p>Maude had the wireless network set up &ldquo;so he can use his phone and iPad in his office&rdquo;, according to a source close to the minister <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/10384226/Francis-Maude-installs-own-Wifi-after-becoming-frustrated-with-Whitehall-IT-systems.html\">quoted by the Daily Telegraph&rsquo;s Georgia Graham</a>, who quotes a source as saying the Cabinet Office&rsquo;s systems are &ldquo;clunky&rdquo; and &ldquo;rubbish&rdquo;.</p> <p>Those \"rubbish\" systems cost about &pound;7,000 per employee, and are designed with government security in mind.</p> <p>But four of the six levels of security classification are to be depreciated in an effort to allow Cabinet Office staff to use more off-the-shelf hardware.</p> <p>Only \"secret\" and \"top secret\" labels will remain unchanged, with 90% of documents reverting to &ldquo;official&rdquo; classification.</p> <p><a href=\"http://countermeasures.trendmicro.eu/government-minister-embraces-the-dark-side/\">Security researcher Rik Ferguson</a> describes Maude's &ldquo;willingness to endanger the security of the parliamentary network, systems and data&rdquo; as &ldquo;incredible&rdquo;.</p> <p>&ldquo;If he really has &lsquo;installed his own Wi-Fi&rsquo; &hellip;&nbsp;then that network segment will not be configured, managed or audited by security experts in the House of Commons, rendering them blind to the the risks it represents,&rdquo; Ferguson adds. &ldquo;Actions like those of Mr Maude demonstrate, yet again, that it&rsquo;s not only the bad guys you have to worry about.&rdquo;</p> <p>&bull; <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/jan/05/computing.egovernment\">The last government's IT overruns ended up costing &pound;2bn</a></strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: in